  "why": "ASDF uses a differential (cross-referencing) oracle rather than a metamorphic oracle, so enforcing semantic equivalence between a mutated input and its original seed is not required (semantic-consistency relative to the seed is therefore not applicable). ASDF does, however, enforce a plausibility/naturalness check on each transformed text by discarding transformed inputs that are not transcribable by at least one ASR (a per-step filter). This is a step-level plausibility enforcement (i.e., it validates each transformed input before adding it), but the paper does not describe controlling semantic similarity relative to the original seed or restricting search to a learned realistic distribution, nor does it account for cumulative distortion across multiple mutation rounds. These characteristics match the metric's “Medium” definition: naturalness enforced between successive mutation steps only (per-step validation) without mechanisms to prevent cumulative drift or to enforce semantic consistency relative to original seeds.",
